<br>
A <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> great leader has a firm direction and solid goals for the guild.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  These goals can range from keeping a family atmosphere to killing the Sleeper (with a little determination LOL).  For the guild leader and all it's members, the goals/direction of the guild must be &quot;fun&quot;. Afterall, we all play EQ for fun.  If the goals and direction aren't clear, members end up doing their own thing.  <br>
<br>
Another thing a great leader does is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> he or she only recruits people that have the same goals as the guild as a whole.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  A lot of guild have trouble here.  They start off with a clear focus, but end up with people that aren't aligned with the focus of the guild.  This leads excessive turnover, people doing their own thing, and people with incorrect expectations of the guild.<br>
<br>
What makes a great guild is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> its own ability to achieve its own goals -- whatever those goals are.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If a guild loses it's family atmosphere that it wanted to maintain, it's not a great guild.  If a guild has goals of killing uber MOBs, but never gets the right levels, classes, and gear together, it's not a great guild.<br>
<br>
