</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ustrykerepeatedly.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stryke Repeatedly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Antisocial Technophobe</span><br>  Posts: 587<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/2/01 9:24:42 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.evenstar.ca/wtf/wtfsmall.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Guild Discussion - Seeking ALL opinions</span><hr size=1> I think Bic and Zaboo covered it, but as a guild leader, I have to say one thing... delegate delegate delegate!  Okay, three things, but they were all the same.  Nothing will destroy a guild's morale faster than having the morale of the guild leader degrade to nothing, and EQ can turn into a job very quickly for somebody who has to run a guild.  My minimum EQ session used to be 2 hours just because that's how long it would take to get through all the tells I received after I had logged on.  I have gained the uncanny ability to maintain about 6 simultaneous conversations, but at a heavy price.  I came to the realization that I wasn't getting a paycheck for this stupid game, so I had to stop treating it like full time employment.  Raventod had the same problem before we merged with the Steel Gladiators, and we had lengthy discussions about it; he co-leads with me now, but even the two of us wouldn't be enough to herd this gaggle of freaks (I mean that in a good way, honest... FREAKS!).<br>
<br>
Now we have committees for grievances, membership, and loot, and those people have complete authority in their respective fields.  Giving up that authority isn't easy, but you have to be prepared to do it.  I can actually group again, and have some catching up to do since some members passed me, but I'm smiling and things are running very smoothly.  You don't necessarily need committees, and you don't need to be all that complicated, but you need to appoint officers for duties and trust them completely in those duties.  If you do it while your guild is young, you won't experience nearly the growing pains you would otherwise should you gain many new members in a short amount of time.<br>
<br>
I guess my point is that whatever your goals either as a guild, or as a leader, structure is important, but not the type of structure one would imagine.  You don't need &quot;houses&quot; or &quot;dynasties&quot;, or class leaders, or anything like that -- those are a neat option, but the kind of structure I mean is just having your officers know their roles and trusting those officers.  If you can get all the mundane guild tasks running on auto-pilot through such structure and delegation, you can work on more important matters, not the least of which is reputation.  No matter what your guild is like internally, make damn sure it's respected externally or you will get nowhere. <p><hr align="center" size="1" COLOR="#006600">
